        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The HCO$^+$(1-0) transitions were detected and resolved in DM~Tau and MWC~480 with PdBI.
These observations were performed  with an angular resolution of $\sim 1.5-5^{''}$
($200-700$~AU at 140~pc). The resulting line brightness is 2-5~K ($\lesssim 0.2-0.5$~Jy).
The higher spatial resolution of $\sim 0.5^{''}$ provided by ALMA is absolutely required to resolve the radial
distribution of CO, HCO$^+$ and DCO$^+$ in disks. 
The outer disk radii are 560--800~AU for these two sources, corresponding
to a diameter of 8 and 11$^{''}$, respectively. However, because of Keplerian
shear, at any velocity, the maximum size in the azimuthal direction is on the
order of $2-3^{''}$. All the flux can thus be recovered by deconvolution, and we
do not need ACA for this experiment.

The flexible correlator setup allows us to observe CO~(3-2) and H$^{13}$CO$^+$~(4-3) in the same baseband window, 
while dust continuum, DCO$^+$~(5-4) and H$^{12}$CO$^+$~(4-3) lines are observed in separate basebands (in the Band~7).
The requested frequency resolution for the all lines is $0.1$~km\,s$^{-1}$ ($122$~kHz). To resolve the line emission at less that 
100~AU scales, the C32-2 ALMA configuration with a spatial resolution of $0.6^{''}$ is required. 
To estimate the intensity of  H$^{13}$CO$^+$~(4-3), which is our primal observing goal and the weakest line in our setup, 
we used the online ALMA OST~tool to produce noisy images from our advanced physico-chemical and LRT disk model of 
MWC~480 (see Fig.~3). The predicted H$^{13}$CO$^+$~(4-3) line flux (with dust emission)
is 1.4~Jy/beam (10~K), however after the dust continuum is subtracted, the lines flux is only $\sim35$~mJy/beam.
To achieve an acceptable S/N detection, 4.2~hours integration (including calibration and other overheads) is 
needed. With 34 antennas and dual polarization, the point source sensitivity is 
about 5~mJy (or 0.15~K) for the 122~kHz resolution. This corresponds
to a detection level of $&gt;7\sigma$ in each channel for H$^{13}$CO$^+$, and higher for the other lines.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
