    <prp:abstract>Evolution of protoplanetary disks and the efficiency of planet formation is regulated by
turbulent viscosity of the gas that depends on ionization structure, which is poorly known.
We propose to determine the ionization structure in inner disks (radii &lt;100 AU), using the unique
sensitivity and resolution of the ALMA interferometer. We aim to observe a low-mass TTau
M1 star (DM Tau) and an intermediate-mass Herbig A4e star (MWC 480) in HCO+ (4-3),
H13CO+ (4-3), CO (3-2) and DCO+ (5-4) in Band 7 at 0.6" spatial resolution, with 9.2 hours of
observing time. HCO+, the most abundant observable polyatomic ion in disks,
will be used to derive the ionization structure provided the gas temperature is known
(which can be probed by optically thick CO and HCO+ lines). The opacity of the
HCO+ (4-3) line will be estimated from the optically thin H13CO+ (4-3)
and DCO+ (5-4) lines.</prp:abstract>
